<font color="#FF0000">DISINFORMATION OR INTELLIGENCE</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jul 29 16:56:32 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
To the professor;<br><br>
Like war stories, actually stories of war if factual.  You never relied upon certain sources for information. Any good intelligence officer in Nam would have told you that the information received was by and far for the most part bogus.  Sometimes, however certain stories had more then one source of origin. <br>
I don't dispute that Ho might have won an election in certain small sections of South Vietnam. <br>
Just because it came from local sources does not mean it was not Communist Propaganda. If the area your talking about was anywhere near Duc Pho east of Highway one, between Chu Lai and Da Nang you maybe right, Uncle Ho might have won an election in that area. <br>
Our company ran operation DeSoto, there in January 1967; it was known that the area was the home of the vice-premier of North Vietnam, a fact in which many locals Vietnamese took great pride. In addition, intelligence sources gave indications that the province chief was a Viet Cong sympathizer, as were many of the refugees. <br>
The villages we discovered were all fake, set up like Hollywood props with old men and women to give the appearance of a genuine working village.  The rice paddies were not functional but built up and covered with deep water. They were set up as actual killing fields, that's why we called the area the Gates of Hell. No one was considered friendly in that area. <br><br>
The common belief among NVA soldiers fighting in the south was that the South Vietnamese civilians were miserable and unhappy, that they were anxiously awaiting liberation. That by going south the NVA soldier was actually protecting the North, as well as fighting to expel the Americans and to reunify the two Vietnams. <br>
Nearly every communist speech the NVA military trainee was subjected too, included the theme that they must go south to &quot;liberate&quot; their fellow countrymen from the American &quot;imperialist.&quot; <br>
That same belief is continuously echoed in many books and magazine articles describing the war today, but it was not true. <br>
 NVA officers captured almost without exception said that the NVA soldier volunteered to go South so as to fight for the cause, that the VC were local supporters, but we now know that was far from the truth.<br><br>
The NVA were also told that non-military people in the United States were supportive of the Revolution and that they were opposed to the conflict and wanted U.S. troops withdrawn from the war zone. Gee, I wonder where they got that idea.<br>
Communist cadre members and high ranking officials bragged about &quot;winning the war on the streets of New York and on the university campuses.&quot;<br>
(they might have even mentioned Long Beach, &lt;G&gt;)<br>
They were told of the barbaric practices of the US fighting men, of capturing them and cutting their intestines out while they were still alive and then there was the most bizarre tale circulating among NVA soldiers that we cut off their ears and eat them. That captured POWs were sometimes placed in a mysterious machine that turned them into negros. (Dark skin was a socioeconomic stigma among the Vietnamese).  <br>
Where we often made mistakes is in believing that removing individuals from the area dropping them into a refugee camp made them supportive of the South Vietnamese government. There were times when a CAC unit was overrun or we engaged the enemy in battle we found those refugees among the dead. <br>
But I can tell you that the enemy, I engaged in battle were not VC, their documents and identification cards were all issued and stamped in Hanoi. I guess I should have cut off their ears to show you that they were NVA and not local jokers.<br>
I traded enough NVA K-bars, uniforms, weapons and equipment to poogues in the rear in Da Nang to fill up several jeeps with whisky, beer, camouflaged uniforms and other equipment we could not obtain by regular military means. I guess I could have just bought those souvenirs from the local villagers since they were VC and not NVA we killed.<br>
Intelligence like many other forms of information services often assumed too many things. Because a captured soldier said he belonged to the 20 bn VC battalion, it was assumed they were VC. In our area, we found dead gooks with NVA uniforms in their backpacks, but they were dressed like VC. Local villagers identified them as NVA not VC. The after action reports list them as VC killed.<br>
The north was quite successful in their political charades and fooled many then and even today. It was all part of the political training and part of Communist propaganda and we still believe it today.<br><br>

<p><code>-- Sorry, I did not ask for them to be NVA and not VC  (Cook, chest beating again.) </code><p>


